<br>
A hand is seen struggling to make it around... struggling to find shelter, a place to hide from a predator.  Further gaze down this lowly trail shows a woman bedraggled in ragged leathers and her many useful weapons that once came to her aide at a point in time merely sticking out of her own flesh.  An assassin by the looks of it.  Her once glistening red hair now caked in dirt and her once tanned skin covered in red blood.  <br>
<br>
She had an early duty the month before to assassinate an apparent ruler of a far away land, but she was only told that the prey was a ruler, nothing more. The thoughts that this prey was merely mortal was a natural underlying thought when given no specifics.  The assassin had left to fulfill the duty to get her pay.... Ha... Tough luck.<br>
<br>
To her surprise.. she spent the next and final month of her life running and trying to evade and avoid her prey which had now turned into the hunter.<br>
<br>
Up in the trees, the leaves were moving furiously as a form seemed to merely glide and fly through the canopy.  The assassin's eyes widened with cravenness as she tried to shuffle out of view.  But... if the hunter was no mortal, she must be something else and would easily spot this.<br>
<br>
The leaves stopped their movement quickly and silence covered the canopy as the tired eyes of the assassin tried to see where the hunter was.  A sudden kick from behind sent the assassin head forward into the dirt.  Pain shot through the assassin as a dagger quickly lodged itself into her side as she tried desperately to turn over.<br>
<br>
A glimmer.. a gleam of malice greeted the assassin and a moment later... nothing but blackness.<br>
<br>
The assassin now lay limp as a ragdoll on the rocky dirt path.<br>
<br>
&quot;Good game... I win.&quot; said the goddess of tragedy with a smirk pressed upon crimson lips. She spent her month in anger to show what happens to those that are foolish enough to try what the dead thing before her had tried.<br>
<br>
Why didn't this goddess think just a little more?  She played a game for a month of hide and seek, and had not bothered to figure out who wanted her dead and who was foolish enough to send an unprepared assassin out after her.<br>
<br>
Here's the clincher...<br>
<br>
Suddenly the forest went quiet and no animal made a sound as a rally of arrows suddenly pierced the godly flesh of Delilah, who was inspecting the inflicted damage of the assassin. Such unexpectedness caught her off guard as she gave a clear and obviously loud yell.  She balled her fists and let out a blast of energy from within the center of her body that sent the arrows out of her flesh and backwards in the air only to begin spinning and soon falling to the earth.<br>
<br>
She spun around to come face to face with an enormous, cloaked figure that took an immediate swing for her gut.  A wide-eyed gasp as the blade of a sword made direct contact and caused a considerable amount of the godly blood to spill from her body.<br>
<br>
A grab at the wound.. it... it penetrated. How??  A kick square in the face sent her flying back, over the dead assassin body and hitting a tree, literally knocking it over.  That boot.. It caused a wound to open on the side of her face, her nose broken.  She had no time to think as the same hooded form suddenly came down from above, apparently having leapt into the air, and slammed the left boot into the gut-wound, crushing her torso completely.  <br>
<br>
With what little breath she had, she lifted her head, spat weakly at the form and exhaled her last breath.  Once shimmering brown eyes rolled backward and her head hit the bark of the tree trunk she was crushed upon.  Limpness took over her body and the blood gushed out from beneath the heavy boot.<br>
<br>
The clouds darkened in the sky and gave a shuddering amount of vibrating thunder with rolling red lightning for a full three minutes before suddenly vanishing in the mere blink of an eye.<br>
<br>
A look back to where the dead goddess lay, and the assassin body and hooded form were gone as if never there...<br>
<br>
A goodbye to tragedy's owner...<br>
<br>
Somewhere... in Asia.... a storm rumbled through the skies as a royal child was born the same moment of the goddess's death.<br>
<br>
